Content-Type: text/plain; charset="Windows-1252"

Hey Everyone,

Do you think green buildings are super cool? Have you ever wanted to see a =
real Living Building Challenge certified building? (there are only 5 in the=
 world!)

Well now is your chance! A group of us will be touring the Smith Bechtel En=
vironmental Classroom at Smith College this Saturday at 10 am. (This means =
leaving here a little after 8 am).

What is the Living Building Challenge you ask? Well, it is a very rigorous =
green building certification that requires your building project to be net-=
zero energy, net-zero water, and contain non-toxic building materials sourc=
ed locally, among many other requirements. If this sounds interesting you s=
hould definitely come and learn more!

If you=92re interested in going let me know and I=92ll add you to the list.

Mariko

[cid:8C1A5ECB-75A1-4DAC-A273-3267620657F7 at olin.edu]

--_000_55DB06484F3743AFB8004FAF4AB8BD41studentsolinedu_

Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable

tl;dr: Annalee Newitz, author and editor of io9.com, is giving a talk next =
Wednesday, April 9th, from 5-6 pm in AC 128.  We have copies of her book, S=
catter, Adapt and Remember: How Humans Will Survive a Mass Extinction, to g=
ive to students for free. iCal attached.


Hey, all-

You'll see this through official channels shortly, but Annalee Newitz (amon=
g other things, the editor of io9.com) is coming to Olin to give a seminar =
next Wednesday, April 9th. She is very kindly donating her honorarium to pu=
rchase copies of her book, so Olin students at the seminar can get a copy f=
or free (while supplies last, obviously).

She's also agreed to participate in the Technology and Culture seminar trad=
ition of having dinner with interested students after her talk. Somewhere i=
n there, I'm sure she'd be happy to sign her book for you.

Full details of the seminar below. Hope to see you there!

Best,

Deb

---

Technology and Culture Seminar Series

How to Save the World with Science...and Journalism

Dr. Annalee Newitz

April 9, 2014, 5-6 pm
AC 128

We know that science and engineering can help humanity survive, sustainably=
, for thousands of years into the future. The problem is that non-scientist=
s often don't understand the new innovations that might make life better fo=
r them and the planet. That's where science journalists come in. We strive =
to explain science to everyone who has never programmed in Scheme, studied =
molecular bonds, or used a robot in the wet lab. But why do we do this, and=
 what are the rewards and pitfalls? Find out more about how science media w=
orks in this talk about writing, researching, and saving the world.

Annalee Newitz writes about science, pop culture, and the future. She's the=
 editor in chief of io9.com, a publication that covers science and science =
fiction, and has over 10 million readers every month. She's the author of S=
catter, Adapt and Remember: How Humans Will Survive a Mass Extinction (Doub=
leday and Anchor), which was nominated for a 2013 LA Times book prize. She'=
s co-editor of the essay collection She's Such A Geek (Seal Press), author =
of Pretend We're Dead: Capitalist Monsters in American Pop Culture (Duke Un=
iversity Press) and is widely published, including in Wired, New Scientist,=
 and Technology Review. She holds a Ph.D. in English and American Studies f=
rom UC Berkeley

Hello all!

TLDR: Perform at Speak. Easy open mic night April 25th at 9pm! Sign Up Here=
<https://docs.google.com/forms/d/14T9BuPA7XuH9BmlRjcl_3v8Bvv8Qgki3Ff-eN3w6g=
ws/viewform>

NTLDR:
As you may have known, Speak. (Olin's spoken word poetry club) is putting o=
n an event! We'll be hosting an Open mic on April 25th at 9pm (location TBD=
). We're looking for acts to sign up and we'd love to hear from you. Yes, I=
 mean you. You know who you are. Anyway, we invite you to sign up with anyt=
hing from stand-up comedy to an acoustic performance and beyond. We'd love =
to hear a bit of poetry as well! Additionally if you're interested in writi=
ng a poem and don't know where to start, come to a  Speak. meeting! We meet=
 on Mondays at 8pm in EH1nn.... And you can sign up for the mailing list to=
o!

I hope you sign up!
Yes. you.
Kay thanks bye,
Kari


--_000_DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40136D36B1E60EXVS01oline_

here about opportunities at 10am tomorrow (Weds) in AC113.  If you can't =
attend and are interested, please let me know and/or talk with our =
Insper visitors any day this week at lunch in the dining hall.

We also still have some room in the pilot class Wednesday at 1pm in =
AC309.  Come help prototype a class (i hear play doh may be involved) =
and pretend like it's Olin's early days....Sign up at the url below.

Questions?  Email me....

Lynn

> Dear Students,
>=20
> Insper is a Brazilian business school launching a new, Olin-like =
engineering program next year.  Nine of their faculty members will be =
visiting Olin next week (3/31-4/3).  Thank you for helping to make them =
welcome.  During the week, they'll be visiting various Olin classes, =
working with Olin students, faculty, and staff in a number of =
capacities, and planning their own curriculum.=20
>=20

> Our Insper colleagues would like to pilot some material that they're =
developing for their curriculum with some of you acting as student =
partners, just like in Olin's early days.  The class itself will be at =
1pm on Wednesday in an AC309.  The class will be followed by a feedback =
session facilitated by Olin Guest Artists Rob Martello and Steve =
Schiffman.  We expect the combined activity to end by 4pm.
>=20

sign up at =

tg/viewform

during our summer or fall semester.  The info session is scheduled for =
10-11am on Wednesday in AC113; for those who cannot attend at that time, =
I know that they'd be happy to discuss opportunities with you at other =
times. =20
>=20

the dining hall, talk to them as they visit your classes, etc.
>=20

=E2=80=8BHey guys,

I think most people on campus know about Rough Draft -- it is a student
venture capital firm that invests 5K - 25K in student-run companies. I've
been involved with Rough Draft for almost a year and many Olin companies
have raised money from Rough Draft, including Technical =E2=80=8BMachine (T=
im, Jon,
Jia, Eric, and Kelsey) and Indico Data Solutions (Slater and Alec)
=E2=80=8Band Lillypad Scales (Molly and Amos).


Let me know if you are ever interested in pitching your ideas to Rough Draf=
t
=E2=80=8B. Its a great way to raise enough money to fund you to work on an =
idea
over the summer instead of take an internship, to design your first round
of PCB boards, pay for server costs, etc.
=E2=80=8B
=E2=80=8B
=E2=80=8B
Jules

  Are you a student entrepreneur who is looking for funding? Roughdraft.vc
is here to help. Is this email not displaying correctly?
View it in your
browser<https://us3.admin.mailchimp.com/templates/*%7CARCHIVE%7C*>
.
 Raise Funding for Your Startup  with Rough Draft VC!


 Are you looking for funding and want to join an amazing network of mentors=
?
  A<http://itunes.apple.com/us/app/alterego-two-factor-security/id465685679=
?mt=3D8>pply
Now <http://www.roughdaft.vc/>   <http://www.roughdraft.vc/>
  <http://www.roughdraft.vc/> Roughdraft.vc
made in boston.

Rough Draft Ventures <http://roughdraft.vc/> is a student partnership
investing in student startups at the earliest stage to help them in their
journey from rough drafts to products in markets. General Catalyst Partners
is a co-founder and funder of our initiative. The
students<http://roughdraft.vc/#partners>
 who are part of Rough Draft Ventures are passionate, smart, driven
technologists who are already catalyzing entrepreneurial activity on their
campuses.
 1. Get up to $25,000Depending upon your need of funds, Roughdraft invests
anywhere between $5-25k. Our average check size is $10k.
2. Decision in 48 hours.Once you *apply,*  <http://roughdraft.vc/#contact>w=
e
set up two student partner meetings, bring you into our office for a pitch,
and let you know our decision within 48 hours. We provide feedback and
support regardless of our decision.
3. Give up zero equity

Roughdraft invests using uncapped convertible debt. Simply speaking, we
don't take any equity and want to be as entrepreneur friendly as possible!
 Meet our student entrepreneurs <http://www.tessel.io/>

Hey guys, I'm in an Entrepreneurial Marketing class at Babson and one of th=
e grad students wanted to ask around at Olin whether there was anyone inter=
ested in developing a mechanical subsystem for a "cold brew coffee on tap" =
product that he is bringing to businesses. His name is Zachary Sloan (zsloa=
n1 at babson.edu<mailto:zsloan1 at babson.edu>) and a description of the business=
 & project is below. Feel free to contact him if you want to learn more, or=
 if you want me to pass on your interest to him, feel free to email me back=
 first.

________________________________
I am looking for an engineering team willing to help me develop a component=
 for my coffee draft system. Our startup is called Drafters Cold Brew Coffe=
e and we are prepping to launch in the next 2 months. Please see the inform=
ation below.

Value Proposition:

Customers now have access to a convenient, refreshing glass of iced coffee =
any time during the work day-all with just a pull of the lever.

*Our cold brewing method delivers a healthier product with 60% less acid th=
an conventionally brewed coffee and our nitrogenated process adds a silky f=
oam to your iced coffee.

*Kegs are conveniently delivered and installed each week.

*Because our coffee is nitrogenated shelf life is > 4 weeks.



Project:
"How can we connect a credit card reader, like Square,
with a mechanical component in the dispenser so that a
completed transaction unlocks the flow of coffee?"

Please let me know if anyone is interested. I will supply unlimited coffee =
for brainstorming sessions!

d:image003.png at 01CF4F54.854D0C20]

--
Zach Sloan
Babson College | F.W. Olin Graduate School of Business
MBA Candidate 2014
845.558.4682 | LinkedIn Profile<http://www.linkedin.com/pub/zach-sloan/16/b=

Emcee: the excellent Brendan Quinlivan

Note - the event will be held in the Dining Hall, so normal dinner will be =
different. All the dining food you know and love will still be there, but t=
he event will be taking up most of the bottom floor.

See you there,
Amanda (on behalf of SERV)

In case you forgot... The dinner will be a simulation of the inequality of =
the resources in the world.  Each person will be given a character ticket a=
s they enter the room to illustrate the lives of those who might live in a =
certain income group.  Each income group will have its own food and seating=
.  In addition to the meal, will have a slide show, speaker, and discussion=
.  Come learn what it feels like to experience food inequality.

From Kai.Austin at students.olin.edu  Mon Apr  7 20:57:16 2014
From: Kai.Austin at students.olin.edu (Kai Austin)
Date: Mon, 7 Apr 2014 20:57:16 -0400
Subject: [Carpediem] Help Design AC Stariwell Art!
Message-ID: <DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40136D3CF7192@EXVS01.olin.edu>

Tur;dle
We need YOU! to help up design the art for the AC stairwell that will be ma=
de on Build Day. Let us know by Friday if you are interested (Before Wednes=
day if you want to come to our meeting with marketing).

Long Version
Due to the location of our Build Day project, it requires much heavier coll=
aboration, correlation, and planning to make things awesome! Help us come u=
p with a design to put in the AC stairwell. Do you need to be an artist? No=
! You will be working with us to come up with what will be put together on =
Build Day. This can either be a base image (to be added to later) or the fi=
nal image itself. We will be working closely with marketing, HDK, and possi=
bly admissions also to design it to work well with Olin and the lovely curv=
atures of our stairs.

The top 4 themes from the survey sent out:

*         A Phoenix (69/95)

*         Cool Geometry/Something Fractal (49/95)

*         The Intersection of Engineering and Beauty (39/95)

*         Wall of plants/The Color Green (35/95)

Comment Summary:
General disapproval for faces of people and creation myths, extra votes for=
 things that express Olin's uniqueness and passions, a concern that painted=
 plants/water would be way too forced and the real thing would be better, a=
nd a call to bring back the stairway piano (I agree with you :( ). Others u=
pon request, but all equally relevant.

Think you have ideas? Want to help design the real thing?
Contact me, Alex Crease, or Eric Schneider by the end of FRIDAY, APRIL 11TH=
.
(Before Wednesday if you want to come to our meeting with marketing).

And don't worry, the rest of you. We do plan on having a "vote for your fav=
orite" session in a few weeks so you are not out of the loop. We're all in =
this together. :)

--_000_DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40136D3CF7192EXVS01oline_

From: Aarti Chellakere
Sent: Wednesday, April 02, 2014 1:24 PM
To: Students - Class of 2014; Students - Class of 2015; Students - Class of=
 2016; Students - Class of 2017
Subject: Fulbright Kick Off Session

Would you like to spend a year doing research, studying or teaching English=
 in one of 150 countries outside the U.S?

Attend the Fulbright<http://us.fulbrightonline.org/about/fulbright-us-stude=
nt-program> kick off session on Wednesday April 9th from 7:45 pm to 9:00 pm=
 in AC 113 to learn more about the program and the application process. ALL=
 students are invited!

Current seniors can apply as alumni and we will support (until you have a d=
octorate degree) and work with you virtually (it has been done in the past)=
.

So RSVP<mailto:aarti.chellakere at olin.edu?subject=3DFulbright%20Kick%20Off%2=
0Session%20-%20RSVP> today!!!


Aarti Chellakere | Assistant Director of Admission and Post Graduate Planni=
ng

1000 Olin Way | Needham, MA 02492

From: William.Saulnier at students.olin.edu (William Saulnier)

Subject: [Carpediem] Dirty PCB: Cheap PCBs For You
Message-ID: <DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40136D2D1603E@EXVS01.olin.edu>

Need a PCB? Need it cheap? Need it fast?

10 5x5 boards are 12 bucks free shipping. 10 10x10 boards are 24 bucks.

I haven't ordered anything from there, but I suppose if you need a PCB for prototyping your new tessel knock off, here's where to go.

http://dirtypcbs.com/

10:00 pm Today, Auditorium

[cid:image003.jpg at 01CF5328.CDB40CC0]

Jean Pierre Jeunet is one of my favorite directors. Most of his films have =
this quirky charm to them. You may be familiar with his most famous film, A=
melie, or may have scrolled past Micmacs or Delicatessen on your Netflix in=
stant queue (however no longer available). The Young and Prodigious T.S. Sp=
ivet looks to be another great addition to his film catalog.

John Arakaki, F.I.L.M. Director
Amanda Lee, Happy Birthday
Travis Lewis, 105 Minute Run Time
Shivam Desai, Potstickers

Subject: [Carpediem] FOR SALE-- 2002 Subaru Forester
Message-ID: <DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40136D2ACAA41@EXVS01.olin.edu>

TLDR: 2002 Subaru Forester; 179k miles; $2700 (negotiable)

Long:
I?m looking to sell my car because I am planning to move into the city soon and owning a car looks like it will be more trouble than it?s worth.  I?ve owned the car for almost three years and it hasn?t given me trouble beyond what you?d expect with a car with its miles.  Great for driving in the snow & moving in and out of Olin (lots of trunk space).  I?d be looking to hand it off any time after graduation, though specific timing is negotiable & if you?d rather get it after the summer that is fine too.  Payment times/ details are also (somewhat) flexible, just let me know what your situation is.

The car is recently inspected with a clean bill of health.  The tires are fairly new (<2000 miles) as well.   No history of accidents that I am aware of.  It lived the first 145 k miles or so of its life in Florida in house with a garage so it is in very good condition for its mileage.  I'm asking for its Blue Book value but I'm open to negotiation. 

Please email me if you are interested in learning more details.  I?d be happy to let you test-drive it if you?d like.  

-Chloe

Hi!

Tl;dr Chicago the musical @ Sorenson this Thursday-Saturday @ 8 for $3.


Claire, Chelsea, Marena, and I are in The Babson Player's production of Chi=
cago the musical this upcoming weekend!

Come see the show, it'll be awesome! It's $3 for B-O-W people and $5 anyone=
 else. It starts at 8PM on Thursday, Friday, and Saturday nights at the Sor=
enson Theater at Babson.

We've been working really hard on the show and it's one of the best sets in=
 recent history. There's lots of dancing, sex, and murder (like my typical =
Tuesday night).

It'll be awesome!


Brian

hard on the show and it&#8217;s one of the best sets in recent history. The=
re&#8217;s lots of dancing, sex, and murder (like my typical Tuesday night)=
.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=3DMsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=3DMsoNor=
mal>It&#8217;ll be awesome!<o:p></o:p></p><p class=3DMsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;<=
/o:p></p><p class=3DMsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=3DMsoNormal>Bri=
an<o:p></o:p></p><p class=3DMsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p></div></body></h=

From: Paige.Cote at students.olin.edu (Paige Cote)
Date: Wed, 9 Apr 2014 17:11:48 -0400

--_000_B676F2E2DC2741A685CE3C17ACEE43E4studentsolinedu_
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"
Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable

There are free books!

Technology and Culture Seminar Series


How to Save the World with Science...and Journalism

Dr. Annalee Newitz


We know that science and engineering can help humanity survive, sustainably=
, for thousands of years into the future. The problem is that non-scientist=
s often don't understand the new innovations that might make life better fo=
r them and the planet. That's where science journalists come in. We strive =
to explain science to everyone who has never programmed in Scheme, studied =
molecular bonds, or used a robot in the wet lab. But why do we do this, and=
 what are the rewards and pitfalls? Find out more about how science media w=
orks in this talk about writing, researching, and saving the world.

Annalee Newitz writes about science, pop culture, and the future. She's the=
 editor in chief of io9.com<http://io9.com/>, a publication that covers sci=
ence and science fiction, and has over 10 million readers every month. She'=
s the author of Scatter, Adapt and Remember: How Humans Will Survive a Mass=
 Extinction (Doubleday and Anchor), which was nominated for a 2013 LA Times=
 book prize. She's co-editor of the essay collection She's Such A Geek (Sea=
l Press), author of Pretend We're Dead: Capitalist Monsters in American Pop=
 Culture (Duke University Press) and is widely published, including in Wire=
d, New Scientist, and Technology Review. She holds a Ph.D. in English and A=
merican Studies from UC Berkeley

--_000_B676F2E2DC2741A685CE3C17ACEE43E4studentsolinedu_

From Slater.Victoroff at students.olin.edu  Wed Apr  9 21:23:45 2014
From: Slater.Victoroff at students.olin.edu (Slater Victoroff)
Date: Wed, 9 Apr 2014 21:23:45 -0400
Subject: [Carpediem] Guided meditation
Message-ID: <DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40136D2D4E7BD@EXVS01.olin.edu>

Sup Carpe,

Way back in the day I used to meditate a lot. It generally made me a much happier person, relieved stress, let me concentrate on work when I needed to, and concentrate on relaxing when I wanted to. After I came to Olin I got busy and kind of stopped doing it as much, which is something that kind of bums me out.

So basically I'm thinking of having a guided meditation session if this is something that would be useful to you and to get me back into regular practice. Time will probably be Saturday or Sunday afternoon for about an hour, either in my room or some room in the AC, or somewhere with more space depending on demand/preference.

Basically just seeing if there would be an interest in something like this. Of course, no experience or anything needed. Email me if this is something that you think would be cool.

Slater

an't wait to see you all there!

From benjamin.kroop at students.olin.edu  Sun Apr 13 19:07:23 2014
From: benjamin.kroop at students.olin.edu (Ben Kroop)
Date: Sun, 13 Apr 2014 19:07:23 -0400
Subject: [Carpediem] MIT Flying Club Spring 2014 Flyout
Message-ID: <CAJiEShh8mP=SP+-ybfteLP9_TRxGpeUV5d2zU5QeRTM=_riySw@mail.gmail.com>

--001a1130cc462d48ec04f6f4a1d6
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8

Hi Carpe People,

Each semester the MIT Flying Club organizes an event where we pair up
pilots and aviation enthusiasts for a flight to an exciting destination. If
you'd like to try out flying in a small plane, learn more about aviation,
or just go on an adventure, this is the event for you!

This semester we'll be flying to Northampton on *Saturday April 26th*.
Northampton is a small town in western Massachusetts with a river, farms,
and a lot of restaurants and stores. It's home to Smith College and is very
close to Hampshire College, Mt. Holyoke, and UMASS Amherst. The flight over
has an interesting mix of scenery. In addition to rivers, rolling hills,
and a small wind farm, we'll pass over the Quabbin Reservoir, the largest
body of water in inland Massachusetts, and the source of most tap water for
the greater Boston area, excluding Cambridge.

*Logistics: *

The flight time is approximately 1.7 hours round trip. For those unfamiliar
with the way flyouts work, we generally depart from airports around Boston
at around 10am, land at our destination in time for lunch, then spend some
time sightseeing before flying back to Boston, arriving back in Cambridge
in the mid to late afternoon. The cost of the flight will be split evenly
within each plane between all passengers and the pilot.

*Cost:*

Most of the planes MIT pilots fly seat up to 4 people, including the pilot,
however most planes end up with 3 people due to weight constraints with
passengers, baggage, and fuel. The standard Cessna 172 or Piper Warrior
costs around $155 per hour to rent, so we expect the total cost of the trip
for each plane to be around $264. As a passenger, you can expect to pay *around
$87 for the entire flight*. The costs will change depending on the plane,
weather, and number of passengers, so once you're assigned to a pilot,
they'll check in with you to give you a more accurate estimate based on the
plane they're flying.

*I recommend signing up early,* because we often do fill all available
passenger seats on flyouts.

*To sign up as a passenger, please fill out this form:* goo.gl/711q1M

If you have any questions, please don't hesitate to email me directly.

Thanks,
Ben

--001a1130cc462d48ec04f6f4a1d6

Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable

From Kai.Austin at students.olin.edu  Tue Apr 15 16:59:16 2014
From: Kai.Austin at students.olin.edu (Kai Austin)
Date: Tue, 15 Apr 2014 16:59:16 -0400
Subject: [Carpediem] WebDev/OWL/Olin.js in the Fall
Message-ID: <DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40137A6B02B91@EXVS01.olin.edu>

--_000_DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40137A6B02B91EXVS01oline_
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"
Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable

This is a shout out to people who are interested in helping to teach:


1.       Have you taken Olin.JS? Are you willing to commit to teaching it a=
gain in the fall? Let me know! You might even be able to take it for credit=
 (note, if you volunteer to teach, it is volunteering...do not expect to be=
 paid for your time).

2.       Have you taken OWL or know a lot about Web Dev? Same question as a=
bove.

Shout out to people who are interested in taking some sort of Web Dev class=
:


1.       Olin.JS lets you work with server side code, databases, and clunck=
y web apps. You will be working with NodeJS, MongoDB and maybeAngular. In t=
he past this has been 4-credit OSS.

2.       OWL focuses on making on online portfolio and "Web literacy" (cras=
h course to the web dev world) -as well as the basics of front end developm=
ent. You will be working with HTML/CSS and Javascript with a heavy focus on=
 design. In the past, this has been 2-credit IS.

Whether or not whatever happens will be an 4 credit OSS (required and grade=
d) or a 2/4 credit IS (not required and pass-no-credit) is highly subject t=
o how many people we can get to teach/be a ninja and how the class is struc=
tured.

--_000_DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40137A6B02B91EXVS01oline_

great suggestions at the elevator pitches but, we don't have the 
resources to do all of them. So I've created a 5 minute long survey to 
gauge what the student body as a whole wants to change in the lounges 
for next year.

the lounges.

Austin

From Logan.Davis at students.olin.edu  Wed Apr 16 15:51:40 2014
From: Logan.Davis at students.olin.edu (Logan Davis)
Date: Wed, 16 Apr 2014 15:51:40 -0400
Subject: [Carpediem] Design a World Championship Robotics MC's Costume!
Message-ID: <DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40137A6A7737F@EXVS01.olin.edu>

Hey Carpe/Helpme,

Next week, I'm going to Los Angeles to work as an MC at the VEX Robotics World Championships. (For those of you who didn't participate in high school robotics: at large competitions, the MC is the face of the event. They do match commentary, work the crowd, and make announcements. MCs usually have a distinctive outfit, e.g. http://files.chickenblog.com/images/domathvegas4210.jpg or http://content.vexrobotics.com/buildblitz/images/Cox.jpg). Anyways, VEX is huge, and this is a pretty great chance to represent/advertise for Olin in the high school engineering community, so I've decided it would be cool to crowdsource what I'll be wearing!

Here are a few constraints/starting points:
1) It would be cool for the outfit to reflect Olin in some way.
2) MCs are explicitly discouraged from wearing costumes - i.e. not this: http://letthemreadvinyl.files.wordpress.com/2011/11/cee-lo.jpg. It should be eye-catching, but not flamboyant or movement-restricting.
3) It needs to be appropriate for all ages. 
4) I don't want to have to cut my hair. Gel/color is fine, albeit a little overdone. 

If you're interested in helping me ideate this thing, send me an email and I'll try to schedule a brief group meeting over the weekend. 

Thanks!

-Logan

From Qun.Zeng at students.olin.edu  Wed Apr 16 21:05:14 2014
From: Qun.Zeng at students.olin.edu (Qun Zeng)
Date: Wed, 16 Apr 2014 21:05:14 -0400
Subject: [Carpediem] Learning & Personal Growth Reflection
Message-ID: <DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40137A6A35023@EXVS01.olin.edu>

Hello,

We're nearing the end of the semester, and it's a good time for reflection. How did you go about learning this semester and did you give yourself enough time to process your learning so that you'll actually retain something worthwhile to yourself? Here's a survey with a few questions: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1IHa5qTbItOM5FTdy-dfTFo15loWuSzarHL1cpLkuU2w/viewform . I'd love to hear your story, but sometimes it's also good to just reflect on how you've grown this semester. Really give yourself the time to do this if it's important to you.

Best,
Annie

Reminder to signup if you missed this the first time it was sent out.  Fair=
ly soon, I'm going to start sending out emails to only those who've filled =
out the survey.

From: Christopher Joyce
Sent: Sunday, March 23, 2014 5:21 PM
To: carpediem at lists.olin.edu; 'outingclub at lists.olin.edu'
Subject: Hiking! WOOO!

[cid:image003.jpg at 01CF5AFA.11220600]TL;DR:  Come hiking between finals and =
expo when you don't have any work.

NTL;R:
Outing club will be organizing a hiking trip to Mt. Monadnock in southern N=
H for the Saturday between finals and expo (May 10, 2014).  Monadnock is a =
great little mountain, not too strenuous, but a very interesting hike.  Vie=
ws from the top are amazing.

Tentative plan is leave Olin around 7am Saturday morning, get to Monadnock =
around 9am, and start hiking.  It's possible that this will even be free, i=
f not, it should come out to less than $10 per person, to cover gas & the p=
ark entrance fee.

Signup is here<https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1TN7a8Z3Znf298n_tudw7lrZgs1v=
jHwwJ9JSaDR5tbSA/edit>, put yourself down if you think there's any chance y=
ou want to go.

I sent out this signup way early so that we could see how many people might=
 want to go, to see what the SAC funding situation might be.  If you put yo=
ur name down, I'll get in touch with you closer to the date of the actual h=
ike with more details.

Also, for interested parties, I'd love to do some weekend hikes to some of =
the closer by rec areas around here as the weather gets better:  Blue Hills=
 is about 20 minutes away, Leominster State Forest is about an hour away.  =
Email me if you'd also be interested in doing some hikes in April, and hope=
fully we can organize something.

Bad news (for me):  I feel crappy.
Good news (for you):  Due to said crappy feelings, I have exactly ZERO desi=
re to organize and/or donate and/or sell the abundance of things I no longe=
r want to keep. So it's all free!

Take some notepads for yourself!
Take some postcards for your cousin!
Take some jeans for your sister!
Take some t-shirts for you great-aunt Nelly to cut up and turn into a quilt=
!
Take it ALL and give it to charity!

I don't really care what you do with it, please just make it GO AWAY!

unt of stuff gets added to the free pile, I'll send another carpe.

From Gabrielle.Waldman-Fried at students.olin.edu  Tue Apr 22 13:59:19 2014
From: Gabrielle.Waldman-Fried at students.olin.edu (Gabrielle Waldman-Fried)
Date: Tue, 22 Apr 2014 13:59:19 -0400
Subject: [Carpediem] Panel on Cooperative Living
Message-ID: <DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40137A732B0F5@EXVS01.olin.edu>

--_000_DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40137A732B0F5EXVS01oline_
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"
Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable

This Wednesday 4/23 (tomorrow!) from 7-8pm there will be a panel discussion=
 on cooperative living in the Anderson Forum at Wellesley College.  A coope=
rative is "an autonomous association of persons united voluntarily to meet =
their common economic, social, and cultural needs and aspirations," accordi=
ng to the International Cooperative Alliance (http://ica.coop<http://ica.co=
op/>). Wellesley College is home to multiple co-ops and Boston has a large =
and flourishing co-op community as well.

>From the Facebook event (https://www.facebook.com/events/1400632110214731/)=
:

"What's the difference between a worker's coop and a housing coop?"
"Sounds like modern day communism."
"Do I have to be a vegetarian?"
"If I join a coop, how can I subvert capitalist and patriarchal power?"

These are all things you can ask us at the Co-op Panel. Join us for an inti=
mate evening where we bring together members of housing cooperatives from W=
ellesley and Boston to tell stories and discuss why we live cooperatively.

Anderson Forum 7pm
Wednesday April 23rd

Bring a mug for fancy tea.

Ask us more questions here<https://www.facebook.com/events/1400632110214731=
/> or on Twitter @WellesleySCoop

~~~~~~Featuring~~~~~~
Moderator: Professor Julie Matthaei, Economics Department
Member of Cornerstone Cohousing

Panelists:
Kayla Northrop '14 - Instead Feminist Coop<https://www.facebook.com/Instead=
FemCoop>
Kennedy Stomps '15 - The Scoop: Wellesley's Sustainability Co-op<https://ww=
w.facebook.com/wcscoop>
Rebecca Leung '13 - Former Bigtop Coop Member and SCoop alum
Gabe Baldwin - Sunrise Cooperative<https://www.facebook.com/SunriseCooperat=
ive> in Jamaica Plain

--_000_DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40137A732B0F5EXVS01oline_

From frances.haugen at gmail.com  Tue Apr 22 14:01:57 2014
From: frances.haugen at gmail.com (Frances Haugen)
Date: Tue, 22 Apr 2014 11:01:57 -0700
Subject: [Carpediem] Interest in re-starting the Yearbook program?
In-Reply-To: <CAHo5XWcDkFCJZpVvYatLTTaY6gSXpDi0Ba8Yi5zJA+n5RtEp-Q@mail.gmail.com>
References: <CAHo5XWcDkFCJZpVvYatLTTaY6gSXpDi0Ba8Yi5zJA+n5RtEp-Q@mail.gmail.com>
Message-ID: <CAHo5XWdS7pHxYu3RQ_6OnagO4HZMnfiKyofn1DuL9=e7dGW4Gw@mail.gmail.com>

--20cf300514bc7578f904f7a56968
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8

TL;DR - I heard the Yearbook is no more. I used to run the Yearbook in a
cash-positive way and I'd be happy to train+mentor folks to re-start the
Olin Yearbook in a sustainable way. Thoughts? Interest?

~~*~~*~~*~~*~~*~~*~~*~~*~~

Hey folks -

A former a Olin Yearbook Editor here (Editions 1, 2, and 3)... I heard
y'all disbanded the yearbook program. What motivated that? Or have I been
misinformed?

I was wondering if there was any interest in rebooting the program in a
lower effort way using print on demand book publishing to minimize
stress/risk?

One of the techniques we used to make the yearbook feasible was that every
student was allocated 1/6th of a page of the yearbook which they could use
for whatever they wanted (within reason) as long as it showed their face in
some way. I was really blown away by the collaborations people did when
they pooled their space, to form full page or two page works. It also meant
the work of making a yearbook was spread out over everyone (or more
accurately, everyone who wanted to participate - the second advantage of
allowing pooling of space) instead of a a handful of overworked folks. The
approach had the added benefit of creating a document that more organically
reflected the community it was meant to document, as it was formed by the
community itself. You still need a couple people to coordinate submissions,
but it's way easier than a traditional yearbook.

The wonderful part of how high quality print on demand printing has gotten
is that if only 15 people want to buy the yearbook, you only have to print
15 copies (though, my senior year we sold like 250 books... so there's
probably at least some latent demand). It also makes it possible to offer
the yearbook in multiple form factors at different price-points (for
example, have a soft and hard cover version).

I would be happy to train in graphic arts+publishing/mentor in execution
anyone who wants to try to do a yearbook again (and even subsidize the
program moderately if other alumni will match me) - it's the kind of
document you end up being really glad someone went to the effort to make
happen when you stumble on it a year or twenty years later, and it's
_really magical_ to get to look through years of yearbooks in an old
college library (as I got to do around colleges about the Boston area), and
see how communities grow and change over the years.

It's too late for this year, but I'd love to help a new crew get things
rolling to be ready for the fall...

Frances
Olin, 2002-2006
Google, 2006-2014
Bored and recuperating from being hospitalized, 2014-present

PS - Anyone know what happened to the old yearbooks from other colleges
that the Olin Yearbook had accumulated? I would love them if they're still
around...

--20cf300514bc7578f904f7a56968
Content-Type: text/html; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable

tl;dr: Talk to me if you want to rock out with ORO next year! Guitarist, ba=
ssist, and violinists especially!

ntl;r: Hey, musicians of Olin! As you may or may not be aware, some people =
are graduating this year! (Weird.) Among them are several members of the Ol=
in Rock Orchestra. In fact, we just played them out on Saturday, so now the=
y've progressed to No Longer In ORO status! That means we're a little defic=
ient now.

That's where you come in! If you've ever dreamed of rocking your brains out=
, now is your chance! No rock experience required, of course. We most direl=
y need guitar, bass, and violin, but if you play something else, we'd love =
to give you a listen!

The commitment is pretty light. We rehearse once a week (currently Fridays)=
 for two hours. Possibly twice a week closer to concert time. We have one o=
r two concerts per semester. Honestly, rehearsals are a lot of fun - it doe=
sn't feel like work. And don't worry, we won't be starting this semester; b=
ut it'd be nice to confirm some players before the next semester starts.

Signing off,
Grieg

From: adventure_club-bounces at lists.olin.edu [mailto:adventure_club-bounces@=
lists.olin.edu] On Behalf Of Shane Skikne
Sent: Thursday, April 17, 2014 3:53 PM
To: studentevents at lists.olin.edu; adventure_club at lists.olin.edu
Subject: [Adventure_Club] Did someone say (fancy) Chocolate?

Are you ready to lift your pinkies in the air and wave them like you just d=
on't care?
This Tuesday at 10:30 pm in EH1, come for the Adventure<https://www.youtube=
.com/watch?v=3Du1_VpJrceJ8> Club fancy chocolate<https://www.youtube.com/wa=
tch?v=3D7kkh22D6UQY> tasting study break!<https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=
=3DMJDkcI5wxHE&feature=3Dyoutu.be&t=3D1s>
We'll have a bunch of great chocolate from all over the world. Everything f=
rom mushroom flavored chocolate to salt and pepper chocolate to good old ch=
ocolate chips.
Rachel Boy and David Pudlo, our local chocolatiers, will be there to teach =
us about chocolate and answer all our questions (about chocolate).

Love,
Adventure Club

P.S. Bring a glass to try the fancy chocolate milk.

FAQ

Can I come and eat as much chocolate as I can fit in my body?
Are you able to? Yes. Should you? We've created this event to have a chance=
 to taste and appreciate a variety of chocolate you might not have had befo=
re. There will be a limited supply of each kind so we ask that you respect =
others and take small pieces and not eat more than your fair share.
Will there be white chocolate? I LOVE WHITE CHOCOLATE!
No.
I LOVE M&M's! Will there be M&M's?
Nope.
Well then, what will you have?
Fancy Milk and dark chocolate in a variety of flavors. (please note, mostly=
 dark chocolate)
What if I don't like chocolate?
Come hang out and stay tuned for the adventure club miracle berry tasting s=
oon!
I knew adventure club was the most attractive club at Olin, but now you thr=
ow events too! How can I join?
Join our mailing list<https://lists.olin.edu/mailman/listinfo/adventure_clu=
b> to hear about all our cool events coming up and adventure office hours.

From christopher.lee at students.olin.edu  Tue Apr 22 22:21:39 2014
From: christopher.lee at students.olin.edu (Chris Lee)
Date: Tue, 22 Apr 2014 22:21:39 -0400
Subject: [Carpediem] Mobile Prototyping OSS
Message-ID: <CAPz2RoT9w2ydgjbPONBgAVcBjBuppWf_DGAXJWYP=CAP7hfJ3A@mail.gmail.com>

--001a113517d27f054604f7ac6471
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="UTF-8"

Clarification for those who don't know of Mobile Prototyping.

It's mobile prototyping on android. We'll most likely be using Android
Studio. It will mainly be a lab/project based class (pairs to teams).

In the past it has been offered as an OSS (4 credits - fulfills your OSS
req.) We won't know when the class will be schedule until sometime later.

However, we need 3 ninjas and 3 student instructors. So far, I believe
there are 2 student instructors interested (including me) and 1 ninja.
(Still looking for volunteers! It'll be fun!)

I'd be happy to answer any further questions. I'm hoping to get a proposal
submitted by the deadline (2 weeks before the end of the semester -
probably with some leeway).


On Tue, Apr 22, 2014 at 9:38 PM, Chris Lee <
christopher.lee at students.olin.edu> wrote:

> Hey all,
> I would love to teach Mobile Prototyping next semester.
> I'm wondering:
> Who would interested in taking this course?
> Who would be interested in teaching this course with me?
> Who would be interested in ninjaing this course?
>
> Let me know soon!
>
> Chris Lee
>

--001a113517d27f054604f7ac6471

From William.Saulnier at students.olin.edu  Wed Apr 23 01:24:00 2014
From: William.Saulnier at students.olin.edu (William Saulnier)
Date: Wed, 23 Apr 2014 01:24:00 -0400
Subject: [Carpediem] Public Speaking OSS - Call to Action
Message-ID: <DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40137A617520C@EXVS01.olin.edu>

tl;dr I'm planning an OSS on Public Speaking. Want to learn how to give better speeches? Want to help teach the course? Let me know with an email.

Howdy Folks,

Remember way back when, as I was talking about public speaking? It's something that's very important to me, and I'm sure is important to you in some way. We communicate through speach as one of our primary forms of interaction, and like it or not you participate in public speaking every day. From conversations with your friends, to that presentation for Bio, Design Nature, RWM, or whatever class you may be taking, to even state dinners or family get togethers or your best friends wedding where you're told to stand up and give a toast with no preparation! 

People often say there are two things they fear. Firstly, it's public speaking. Secondly, it's death. When asked why in that order, they claim it is because dead people don't have to give speeches. I'm in the process of designing an OSS to eliminate that fear from your list. (Well, possibly both. You never know.) Here's the facts:

1) It will be graded as a traditional 4 credit OSS, with potential options for a 2 credit OSS or even a 4/2 credit IS. This is important because it provides incentive and drive to practice and get up and speak. Rest assured that grading will be as transparent and as clear as possible.

2) You will be engaging in public speaking. Every class. Practice makes perfect, and everyone needs practice.

3) It will be fun! We'll cover so much over our time, from toasts to lectures to poster presentations to improv. 

So, this is a call to action for everyone. Face the fears of speaking in public. Banish the ums and ahs and likes from your speech! Understand what makes a good powerpoint! Learn about visual aids, what your hands should be doing, where you should stand and why, how to combat anxiety and how to think on your feat! How to pace yourself and play your audience, and how to go forth with the confidence to be undaunted when you need to speak in front of an audience! Email me if you think this is something you want to see happen!

I'm also looking for like minded public speakers who can jump in as teachers and fellow NINJAs. No formal experience with public speaking needed, but a willingness to collaborate on lesson planning, the ability to lead small groups, and the drive to make this happen are needed more than ever!

Never be fearful of your next presentation, design review, or inspirational speech again! Join me, the potential future team, and the rest of Olin in proving that engineers can communicate to the world all the fun, awesome, and innovative stuff we do.

-William

From Kai.Austin at students.olin.edu  Wed Apr 23 11:45:23 2014
From: Kai.Austin at students.olin.edu (Kai Austin)
Date: Wed, 23 Apr 2014 11:45:23 -0400
Subject: [Carpediem] (Update): WebDev/OWL/Olin.js in the Fall
In-Reply-To: <DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40137A6B02B91@EXVS01.olin.edu>
References: <DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40137A6B02B91@EXVS01.olin.edu>
Message-ID: <DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40137A74A0A10@EXVS01.olin.edu>

Hey everyone,

So here's the thing. If I am going to teach OlinJS in the Fall, I need at least 3 instructors (with no more than 16 credits, including the OSS, plus prior ninja experience) and 3 ninjas (with no more than 18 credits, including a 2-credit IS they sign up for to teach).
If I am going to teach OWL in the Fall, I need a minimum of 2 instructors and 2 ninjas.
Committed for sure by the end of next week. 
Unfortunately, I do not think either will work out for the Fall semester unless people are stoked and want to jump on board, so I sincerely apologize again for getting this out late. Will be aiming again (specifically OlinJS) for the spring, as those who did indicate some interest said that would likely be a better time....

Cheers,
- Kai

From: carpediem-bounces at lists.olin.edu [carpediem-bounces at lists.olin.edu] On Behalf Of Kai Austin
Sent: Tuesday, April 15, 2014 4:59 PM
To: carpediem at lists.olin.edu
Subject: [Carpediem] WebDev/OWL/Olin.js in the Fall

This is a shout out to people who are interested in helping to teach:


1.       Have you taken Olin.JS? Are you willing to commit to teaching it again in the fall? Let me know! You might even be able to take it for credit (note, if you volunteer to teach, it is volunteering?do not expect to be paid for your time).

2.       Have you taken OWL or know a lot about Web Dev? Same question as above.

Shout out to people who are interested in taking some sort of Web Dev class:


1.       Olin.JS lets you work with server side code, databases, and cluncky web apps. You will be working with NodeJS, MongoDB and maybeAngular. In the past this has been 4-credit OSS.

2.       OWL focuses on making on online portfolio and ?Web literacy? (crash course to the web dev world) ?as well as the basics of front end development. You will be working with HTML/CSS and Javascript with a heavy focus on design. In the past, this has been 2-credit IS.

Whether or not whatever happens will be an 4 credit OSS (required and graded) or a 2/4 credit IS (not required and pass-no-credit) is highly subject to how many people we can get to teach/be a ninja and how the class is structured.

For anyone wanting to teach OlinJS, don't know how close you're going to
stick with the old curriculum, but if you do I recommend ripping out
everything about mongoose and using mongojs instead.


On Wed, Apr 23, 2014 at 11:45 AM, Kai Austin
<Kai.Austin at students.olin.edu>wrote:

> Hey everyone,
>
> So here's the thing. If I am going to teach OlinJS in the Fall, I need at
> least 3 instructors (with no more than 16 credits, including the OSS, plus
> prior ninja experience) and 3 ninjas (with no more than 18 credits,
> including a 2-credit IS they sign up for to teach).
> If I am going to teach OWL in the Fall, I need a minimum of 2 instructors
> and 2 ninjas.
> Committed for sure by the end of next week.
> Unfortunately, I do not think either will work out for the Fall semester
> unless people are stoked and want to jump on board, so I sincerely
> apologize again for getting this out late. Will be aiming again
> (specifically OlinJS) for the spring, as those who did indicate some
> interest said that would likely be a better time....
>
> Cheers,
> - Kai
>
> ________________________________________
> From: carpediem-bounces at lists.olin.edu [carpediem-bounces at lists.olin.edu]
> On Behalf Of Kai Austin
> Sent: Tuesday, April 15, 2014 4:59 PM
> To: carpediem at lists.olin.edu
> Subject: [Carpediem] WebDev/OWL/Olin.js in the Fall
>
> This is a shout out to people who are interested in helping to teach:
>
>
> 1.       Have you taken Olin.JS? Are you willing to commit to teaching it
> again in the fall? Let me know! You might even be able to take it for
> credit (note, if you volunteer to teach, it is volunteering...do not expect
> to be paid for your time).
>
> 2.       Have you taken OWL or know a lot about Web Dev? Same question as
> above.
>
> Shout out to people who are interested in taking some sort of Web Dev
> class:
>
>
> 1.       Olin.JS lets you work with server side code, databases, and
> cluncky web apps. You will be working with NodeJS, MongoDB and
> maybeAngular. In the past this has been 4-credit OSS.
>
> 2.       OWL focuses on making on online portfolio and "Web literacy"
> (crash course to the web dev world) -as well as the basics of front end
> development. You will be working with HTML/CSS and Javascript with a heavy
> focus on design. In the past, this has been 2-credit IS.
>
> Whether or not whatever happens will be an 4 credit OSS (required and
> graded) or a 2/4 credit IS (not required and pass-no-credit) is highly
> subject to how many people we can get to teach/be a ninja and how the class
> is structured.
>
> --
> You received this message because you are subscribed to the Google Groups
> "OlinJS" group.

Details:
We need you help coming up with snazzy designs for the AC stairwell! We are=
 looking to go for an image made from several fragments (examples attached:=
 Pheonix1). Keep in mind the size of your image. Think minimalism. Pieces w=
ill be finalized and fitted onto stickers with 2'x2' dimensions on Build Da=

ll" for sample wall to work with, Pheonix-Wall for an idea, though this is =
slightly larger than it would be). If you can make a design that goes up a =
few levels, then you are a divine being.

'em in asap! Build Day is next Friday, peoples! Be excited!

Subject: [Carpediem] Selling my bike
Message-ID: <DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40137A692539D@EXVS01.olin.edu>

Hi Carpe,

It's that time of year. I'm looking to sell my bike. I don't use it as much as I should, and I want to give it a better home.

It's a Dynamic Tempo Transit 8, and it has a driveshaft, which is kinda neat. See:http://www.dynamicbicycles.com/bicycles/tempotransit8.php

The frame size is 19", which is about right for a 5'7"-6'0" person.

Price is negotiable, just let me know if your interested, and we could work something out.

Cheers,
Alethea

From: carpediem-bounces at lists.olin.edu [mailto:carpediem-bounces at lists.olin=
.edu] On Behalf Of Gregory Edelston
Sent: Tuesday, April 22, 2014 2:07 PM
To: carpediem at lists.olin.edu
Subject: [Carpediem] Rock the fuck out!

tl;dr: Talk to me if you want to rock out with ORO next year! Guitarist, ba=
ssist, and violinists especially!

ntl;r: Hey, musicians of Olin! As you may or may not be aware, some people =
are graduating this year! (Weird.) Among them are several members of the Ol=
in Rock Orchestra. In fact, we just played them out on Saturday, so now the=
y've progressed to No Longer In ORO status! That means we're a little defic=
ient now.

That's where you come in! If you've ever dreamed of rocking your brains out=
, now is your chance! No rock experience required, of course. We most direl=
y need guitar, bass, and violin, but if you play something else, we'd love =
to give you a listen!

The commitment is pretty light. We rehearse once a week (currently Fridays)=
 for two hours. Possibly twice a week closer to concert time. We have one o=
r two concerts per semester. Honestly, rehearsals are a lot of fun - it doe=
sn't feel like work. And don't worry, we won't be starting this semester; b=
ut it'd be nice to confirm some players before the next semester starts.

Signing off,
Grieg

--_000_DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40137A757D42AEXVS01oline_

Heylo there!

You may have heard word floating around about the "Design Hackathon" that's=
 going to happen Sept. 12-13, the second weekend of fall semester.

Confirmation - this not a rumor!  What we've informally dubbed the "designa=
thon" will focus on user-oriented design in the pre-college educational set=
ting.  Essentially, you spend 24 hours with ~100 designers, artists, and en=
gineers from nearby colleges to develop an idea on how to innovate in this =
space.

We're still fleshing out the details, but we'd love to hear your input!  ht=
tp://goo.gl/FwxEQ2

Feel free to contact myself, Madison, Celine, or Jennifer Wei if you've fur=
ther questions!

Happy finals time.

Liani on behalf of the Foundry

Hey folks,

There's a startup called mimiopen that's focused on connecting high school =
students trying to learn about colleges with students who go to those colle=
ges.  It's run by some really nice folks, and they'd love to hire some stud=
ents to represent Olin.  It looks like very much a part-time gig - my impre=
ssion is a couple of hours a week max. (That's only my impression, though -=
 if you're interested I'd confirm that with them)

If you want to learn more about them, check out mimiopen.com, and if you'd =
like work for them, let me know so I can put you in touch!

-Rachel

Hey all!

We all have skeletons in the closet, and by skeletons, we mean the decaying=
 remains of old projects from various classes or pursuits that have outlive=
d their glory demo days. Well, there is a Build Day project to scavenge par=
ts and retire those beloved works! If you have an old project stored in the=
 POE room, your room, or elsewhere on campus, that you'd like to return to =
the circle of life, dig them up now and drop by the 3rd floor AC on Build D=
ay. We'll be there all day. Alternatively, if you like categorically destro=
ying things, help us take things apart!

Let us know if you have any questions or concerns!

Best,
The POE Workspace Team

F.I.L.M. and Anime Club Present: Redline<https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3D=
2t26m_Q6ENo>
10:00 pm Today, Auditorium

[cid:image001.jpg at 01CF63B1.91B6EF00]

FILM and Anime Club are collaborating tonight to present Redline. This is a=
 2009 Japanese sci-fi anime film directed by Takeshi Koike. The film has be=
en praised for its impressive visuals, soundtrack, and all around intense l=
evel of excitement.

John Arakaki, 2013-2014 F.I.L.M. Director
Zachary Homans, Anime Club President
Amanda Lee, 2014-2015 F.I.L.M. Director
Travis Lewis, 102 Minute Run Time and Takoyaki

MAKE-YOUR-OWN ORGANIC PIZZA NIGHT!!!!

Are you interested in SUSTAINABILITY? Do you like FOOD? Well then the newly=
-formed Earth and Table (EAT) club is the place for you!

Come join us for our kick-off event to learn more about the club and enjoy =
some stellar, homemade organic pizza! Thursday May 8th at 6 pm in the EH ki=
tchen.

The topic of conversation will revolve around =93What is organic food?"

Please R.S.V.P. via this<https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1fwFaY-u-JD5bh4ihG=
aEZw5nLasErO_rjZCR3WvqzhvI/viewform?usp=3Dsend_form> form if you plan on at=
tending. Gluten free options will be made available upon request.

Mariko

Hello all!

Friday, May 9th is the annual Faculty and Staff Party for the senior class,
and we are looking to hire people to babysit for the professors and to
provide rides. This is an awesome way to participate in a party that you
young folks don't get to attend until you're seniors. You will get paid!

If you're interested, let me know!

--Noam

Hi Oliners!
President Miller sent this email out not too long ago about the President's=
 Council meeting on Friday May 9th. Aditi and I attended this meeting last =
semester, and we highly recommend that you consider attending on May 9th. I=
t was extremely exciting to meet many of Olin's supporters from a wide vari=
ety of different backgrounds -alumni, leaders of the world's most prominent=
 companies, world renowned professors, and trustees just to name a few! If =
you want to rub elbows with the administration and listen to some brilliant=
 minds, take a look at the email below and RSVP.

Democratically yours,
Ian, Aditi, and CORe

From: President Miller
Sent: Wednesday, April 16, 2014 4:40 PM
To: Students - All Olin Students
Cc: Nancy Sullivan; Richard K. Miller; Lauren K. Taaffe; Carole Perrin; Mar=
guerite Burke
Subject: Olin College President's Council Meeting - Friday, May 9, 2014

Dear Students,

I would welcome student participation at the upcoming President's Council m=
eeting on Friday, May 9, 2014.

What is the President's Council?  Who are the President's Council members?
http://www.olin.edu/about/presidents-council/

"Some of the most distinguished names in engineering education have been re=
cruited to serve on a special advisory board for the college. The President=
's Council is a group of distinguished advisors who have volunteered their =
time to counsel the president on a full range of issues relating to curricu=
lum, student life, administration and finance, governance, admission and ot=
her topics important to the college. The Council meets two times per year."=
  Olin Trustees also participate in the President's Council meeting
http://www.olin.edu/about/board-trustees/

There are a limited number of openings for current students to join this ev=
ent.  If you are interested, and available, please send Carole Perrin<mailt=
o:carole.perrin at olin.edu> an email paragraph saying why you would like to a=
ttend.  First preference will be given to those whose email is received by =
10:00 am, (Friday, May 2nd). You are welcome to participate as your interes=
t and time allow.

PLEASE include your "all important" name badge information in your reply.  =
(For example, preferred name, class year, involvements and/or major, hometo=
wn - Carole Perrin '14, SERV Coordinator, Economics, Lynnfield, MA.)
Students who participate during the breakout sessions will be asked to be s=
cribes.  (You will need your laptop or similar device.)

I will be emailing the "white paper" for this meeting soon.

Rick

ome pizza. I will be getting a delivery from Domino's Pizza (menu<https://o=
rder.dominos.com/en/pages/order/menu.jsp>). It will be delivered to the Aca=
demic Center. If you want to order, please write an order on a sticky note =
on the "Help" board of the 2nd studio. (If you don't want to schlepp out to=
 the AC, I guess you can email an order, too.) Cash and venmo gladly accept=
ed.



mitch
